"Adachi K., Chung S.H., Buseck P.R.","Shapes of soot aerosol particles and implications for their effects on climate",2010,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","115","15", D15206,"","",,,10.1029/2009JD012868,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955862427&partnerID=40&md5=7c86f5ec4267c54c0dc494b0aa0bbeac","School of Earth and Space Exploration, Arizona State University, Tempe, AZ 85287, United States; Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry, Arizona State University, Tempe, AZ 85287, United States; Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Washington State University, Pullman, WA 99164, United States","Adachi, K., School of Earth and Space Exploration, Arizona State University, Tempe, AZ 85287, United States, Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry, Arizona State University, Tempe, AZ 85287, United States; Chung, S.H., Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Washington State University, Pullman, WA 99164, United States; Buseck, P.R., School of Earth and Space Exploration, Arizona State University, Tempe, AZ 85287, United States, Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry, Arizona State University, Tempe, AZ 85287, United States","Soot aerosol particles (also called light-absorbing, black, or elemental carbon) are major contributors to global warming through their absorption of solar radiation. When embedded in organic matter or sulfate, as is common in polluted areas such as over Mexico City (MC) and other megacities, their optical properties are affected by their shapes and positions within their host particles. However, large uncertainties remain regarding those variables and how they affect warming by soot. Using electron tomography with a transmission electron microscope, three-dimensional (3-D) images of individual soot particles embedded within host particles collected from MC and its surroundings were obtained. From those 3-D images, we calculated the optical properties using a discrete dipole approximation. Many soot particles have open, chainlike shapes even after being surrounded by organic matter and are located in off-center positions within their host materials. Such embedded soot absorbs sunlight less efficiently than if compact and located near the center of its host particle. In the case of our MC samples, their contribution to direct radiative forcing is ∼20% less than if they had a simple core-shell shape, which is the shape assumed in many climate models. This study shows that the shapes and positions of soot within its host particles have an important effect on particle optical properties and should be recognized as potentially important variables when evaluating global climate change. Copyright 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric aerosols; Biogeochemistry; Biological materials; Climate models; Dust; Electric impedance tomography; Global warming; Optical properties; Organic compounds; Soot; Sun; Transmission electron microscopy; 3-D image; Absorption of solar radiation; Chain-like; Core-shell shape; Direct radiative forcing; Discrete dipole approximation; Electron tomography; Elemental carbon; Global climate changes; Host materials; Megacities; Mexico City; Organic matter; Particle optical properties; Polluted area; Soot aerosols; Soot particles; Transmission electron microscope; Three dimensional; absorption; aerosol; climate effect; climate modeling; global warming; light; optical property; organic matter; particle size; radiative forcing; solar radiation; soot; sulfate; three-dimensional modeling; tomography; transmission electron microscopy; uncertainty analysis; Federal District [Mexico]; Mexico City; Mexico [North America]",,,,,,"Adachi, K., Buseck, P.R., Internally mixed soot, sulfates, and organic matter in aerosol particles from Mexico City (2008) Atmos. Chem. Phys., 8, pp. 6469-6481; Adachi, K., Chung, S.H., Friedrich, H., Buseck, P.R., Fractal parameters of individual soot particles determined using electron tomography: Implications 